Malaysia Stocks: Kencana Petroleum, KL Kepong, Silk Holdings

-- B y   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-07-12T09:15:28Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-12/malaysia-stocks-kencana-petroleum-eastern-and-oriental-silk.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  Malaysia  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 5 p.m. close in  Kuala
Lumpur .  The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index fell 10.48 points, or
0.7 percent, to 1,578.10, its biggest drop since June 13.  Plantation stocks:  Kuala Lumpur Kepong Bhd. (KLK)  
dropped 1.8 percent to 22.40 ringgit, the most since April 11.
 PLS Plantations Bhd. (PLS)   fell 5 percent to 1.15 ringgit and
 TH Plantations Bhd. (THP)   slid 1 percent to 2.08 ringgit.  Malaysian palm-oil prices may fall below 3,000 ringgit
($991) a metric ton this month as consumers may defer purchases
in anticipation of lower prices, CIMB Investment Bank Bhd. said
in a report today.  Kencana Petroleum Bhd. (KEPB)   rose 5 percent to 2.94
ringgit, a record close, after receiving a proposal to merge
with  SapuraCrest Petroleum Bhd. (SCRES)   in an 11.9 billion
ringgit deal to create Malaysiaâ€™s largest listed oilfield
services company by assets. SapuraCrest gained 0.2 percent to
4.50 ringgit.        Silk Holdings Bhd. (SIB)  , an oil and gas services
provider, climbed 11 percent to 29.5 sen, the steepest rise
since Oct. 29, 2009, after winning four charter contracts valued
at 39.8 million ringgit to supply vessels to Petronas Carigali
